{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12340"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12340"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.02,0.69,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4860"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64014"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1075"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 23-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of severe, continuous itching that keeps him awake throughout the night. The itching started in his groin and has spread to his arms and legs and most noticeably between his fingers. His mother also has a similar rash which is very itchy. On examination, he has a vesicular rash, this being most apparent on his hands and groin. There are blackish spots on his hands and legs and burrows seen as well (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnostic investigations would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skin biopsy","Serum IgE levels","Patch testing","Microscopic examination of skin scrapings","Wood\u0027s lamp examination"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has scabies. Scabies is the result of a skin infestation by the Sarcoptes mite and the subcutaneous burrowing of the parasite and subsequent skin reaction leads to intense itching. There is often a widespread papular rash as a reaction to the infestation and this is associated with multiple excoriation marks. Burrows can be seen, which are linear palpable ridges on the skin with black specks. Typically several individuals who have been in close contact (households, schools) will be affected simultaneously. Secondary infection can occur due to scratching. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroscopic examination of skin scrapings\u003C/strong\u003E is the most direct method to confirm a diagnosis of scabies. Skin scrapings from burrows or vesicles are examined under a microscope to identify the presence of mites, eggs, or fecal pellets, which are indicative of scabies infestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used to diagnose scabies, as it is more invasive and less specific than direct microscopic examination. It may be used in atypical cases where other diagnoses are being considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatch testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to identify allergens responsible for contact dermatitis and is not relevant in diagnosing scabies, which is caused by a mite infestation rather than an allergic reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWood\u0027s lamp examination\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose certain fungal and bacterial infections of the skin, but it is not useful for diagnosing scabies, as the mites do not fluoresce under ultraviolet light.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum IgE levels\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in various allergic conditions, but they are not specific for scabies and do not aid in its diagnosis. The itching in scabies is due to a hypersensitivity reaction to the mites and their products, but serum IgE levels are not used for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scabies is a skin condition caused by the mite Sarcoptes scabiei, variety hominis.","Itching may persist even after all mites have been eliminated due to the hypersensitivity reaction.","Microscopic examination of skin scrapings can confirm the diagnosis of scabies."],"references":["Murray RL, Crane JS. Scabies. 2023 Jul 31. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31335026. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31335026/","Uzun S, Durdu M, Y\u00fcrekli A, M\u00fclayim MK, Akyol M, Velipa\u015fao\u011flu S, Harman M, Taylan-\u00d6zkan A, \u015eavk E, Demir-Dora D, D\u00f6nmez L, Gazi U, Akta\u015f H, Akt\u00fcrk A\u015e, Demir G, G\u00f6ktay F, G\u00fcrel MS, G\u00fcrok NG, Karada\u011f AS, K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck \u00d6S, Turan \u00c7, Ozden MG, Ural ZK, Zorbozan O, Mumcuo\u011flu KY. Clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of scabies. Int J Dermatol. 2024 Dec;63(12):1642-1656. doi: 10.1111/ijd.17327. Epub 2024 Jun 23. PMID: 38922701; PMCID: PMC11589009. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38922701/","Sunderk\u00f6tter C, Wohlrab J, Hamm H. Scabies: Epidemiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2021 Oct 15;118(41):695-704. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.m2021.0296. PMID: 34615594; PMCID: PMC8743988. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34615594/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64014"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12340"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20609"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20609"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YWj3p3v7BL5K7LJCCLu8wmn5TYORbB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YWj3p3v7BL5K7LJCCLu8wmn5TYORbB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":746,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64014"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:03:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:05:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4860"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd